===============================================================================
PROJECT STRUCTURE (CANONICAL)
===============================================================================

app/
├── Domain/
│   ├── {Module}/
│   │   ├── Actions/                  # Core business logic — infra agnostic
│   │   │                             # Can be AsController·AsJob·AsListener·AsCommand
│   │   ├── Web/
│   │   │   ├── Actions/              # HTMX adapters — MUST use HtmxOrchestrator
│   │   │   ├── Views/                # Blade templates + HTMX partials
│   │   │   └── Components/           # Blade components for this module
│   │   ├── Api/
│   │   │   └── Actions/              # JSON adapters — thin, delegates to Core
│   │   ├── Data/                     # Spatie Laravel Data DTOs
│   │   │   ├── {Model}FormData       # Mutation input + validation
│   │   │   ├── {Model}TableData      # Read output — MUST have fromModel()
│   │   │   ├── {Model}FilterData     # Query scope / search parameters
│   │   │   ├── {Model}ResourceData   # API output shape
│   │   │   ├── {Model}UpsertData     # Create-or-update payload
│   │   │   ├── {Model}CollectionData # Typed collection — MUST use Lazy
│   │   │   └── {Model}PayloadData    # Job / event payload
│   │   ├── Pipelines/                # Laravel Pipeline pipe classes
│   │   ├── ValueObjects/             # final readonly — validated in constructor
│   │   ├── Enums/                    # Backed enums (string|int)
│   │   └── Models/                   # Anemic Eloquent — scopes, casts, relations ONLY
│   │
│   └── Shared/
│       ├── Actions/                  # Cross-module, polymorphic use cases
│       ├── Data/                     # Shared DTOs and contracts
│       ├── Events/                   # Domain events for cross-context communication
│       ├── Notifications/            # NotificationService (email + telegram)
│       ├── ValueObjects/             # Shared value objects (Money, DateRange…)
│       └── Enums/                    # Shared backed enums
│
└── Support/
    └── HtmxOrchestrator.php          # HTMX response builder (trait)

routes/modules/{module}.php           # One flat file per module

===============================================================================
PRINCIPLE 1 — CORE ACTIONS
===============================================================================

Namespace  : App\Domain\{Module}\Actions
Rules:
  - 100% infrastructure agnostic (no HTTP, no View, no HTMX, no redirect)
  - Input  : Spatie Data DTOs or primitives — NEVER Illuminate\Http\Request
  - Output : Spatie Data DTOs or primitives — NEVER Response objects
  - MUST   : use AsAction; + public function handle(...)

lorisleiva full power — use any combination of traits on a single Action:
  - AsJob        → MyAction::dispatch($dto)  dispatches to queue
  - AsListener   → listens to a domain event, handle() is the handler
  - AsCommand    → registers as artisan command, handle() is the command body
  - AsController → only on Web/Api Actions (Core Actions avoid HTTP layer)

Extra methods allowed on Core Actions (lorisleiva API):
  rules()                   → validation rules when used as controller/job
  authorize()               → authorization logic
  prepareForValidation()    → normalize input before validation
  asJob(JobDispatch $job)   → customize job behavior
  getJobMiddleware()        → job middleware

EXAMPLE:
```php
<?php
declare(strict_types=1);
namespace App\Domain\Assets\Actions;

use Lorisleiva\Actions\Concerns\AsAction;
use App\Domain\Assets\Data\AssetUpsertData;
use App\Domain\Assets\Data\AssetTableData;
use App\Domain\Assets\Models\Asset;

final class UpsertAsset
{
    use AsAction;

    public function handle(AssetUpsertData $data): AssetTableData
    {
        $asset = Asset::updateOrCreate(['id' => $data->id], $data->toArray());

        return AssetTableData::fromModel($asset);
    }
}
```

===============================================================================
PRINCIPLE 2 — WEB ACTIONS
===============================================================================

Namespace  : App\Domain\{Module}\Web\Actions
Rules:
  - Thin adapter: validate → call Core Action → return HTMX partial
  - MUST use HtmxOrchestrator trait
  - NEVER manipulate HX-* headers directly — use orchestrator methods only
  - NEVER import or use Models — only DTOs
  - NEVER put business logic here — 100% delegated to Core Actions
  - Mutation actions (Store/Upsert) MUST declare ProtectAgainstSpam middleware

EXAMPLE:
```php
<?php
declare(strict_types=1);
namespace App\Domain\Assets\Web\Actions;

use Lorisleiva\Actions\Concerns\AsAction;
use App\Support\HtmxOrchestrator;
use App\Domain\Assets\Actions\UpsertAsset;
use App\Domain\Assets\Data\AssetUpsertData;
use Spatie\Honeypot\ProtectAgainstSpam;

final class StoreAsset
{
    use AsAction;
    use HtmxOrchestrator;

    public function getControllerMiddleware(): array
    {
        return [ProtectAgainstSpam::class];
    }

    public function handle(AssetUpsertData $data): \Illuminate\Http\Response
    {
        $result = UpsertAsset::run($data);

        return $this->hxView('assets.partials.row', ['asset' => $result]);
    }
}
```

===============================================================================
PRINCIPLE 3 — SPATIE LARAVEL DATA (FULL POWER)
===============================================================================

All DTOs MUST be: `final readonly class` extending `Spatie\LaravelData\Data`

Allowed suffixes — no other naming is permitted:
  FormData        mutation input + validation rules (create / update)
  TableData       read output — MUST have static fromModel(Model $m): self
  UpsertData      create-or-update payload
  FilterData      query scope / search parameters
  ResourceData    API output shape
  CollectionData  typed collection — MUST use Lazy::create(fn() => ...)
  PayloadData     job or event payload

Full Spatie Data feature set — USE these, do not work around them:

VALIDATION ATTRIBUTES:
  #[Rule('required|string|max:255')]
  #[Min(1)], #[Max(100)], #[Email], #[Uuid], #[In(['a','b'])]
  #[Exists('table', 'column')], #[Unique('table', 'column')]

CASTING:
  #[WithCast(CarbonCast::class)]
  #[WithCast(EnumCast::class, MyEnum::class)]
  #[WithCast(DateTimeInterfaceCast::class, format: 'Y-m-d')]

OUTPUT / INPUT MAPPING:
  #[MapOutputName('snake_case_key')]
  #[MapInputName('camelCaseKey')]
  #[MapName(SnakeCaseMapper::class)]

COMPUTED & HIDDEN:
  #[Computed]   for derived properties (set in constructor, not from input)
  #[Hidden]     exclude from serialization (passwords, internal IDs)

COLLECTIONS:
  public DataCollection $items  — use DataCollection<int, MyTableData>
  combine with Lazy::create(fn() => MyTableData::collect($model->items))

PARTIAL OUTPUT (API / HTMX fragments):
  $dto->only('id', 'name')
  $dto->except('internal_field')
  $dto->wrap('data')

EXAMPLE — TableData with fromModel:
```php
<?php
declare(strict_types=1);
namespace App\Domain\Assets\Data;

use App\Domain\Assets\Models\Asset;
use Spatie\LaravelData\Data;
use Spatie\LaravelData\Attributes\MapOutputName;

final readonly class AssetTableData extends Data
{
    public function __construct(
        public int    $id,
        public string $code,
        public string $name,
        #[MapOutputName('created_at')]
        public string $createdAt,
    ) {}

    public static function fromModel(Asset $asset): self
    {
        return new self(
            id        : $asset->id,
            code      : $asset->code,
            name      : $asset->name,
            createdAt : $asset->created_at->toDateTimeString(),
        );
    }
}
```

EXAMPLE — FormData with validation:
```php
<?php
declare(strict_types=1);
namespace App\Domain\Assets\Data;

use Spatie\LaravelData\Data;
use Spatie\LaravelData\Attributes\Validation\{Rule, Max, Min};

final readonly class AssetFormData extends Data
{
    public function __construct(
        #[Rule('sometimes|integer')]
        public ?int   $id,
        #[Max(50)]
        public string $code,
        #[Max(255)]
        public string $name,
    ) {}
}
```

EXAMPLE — CollectionData with Lazy:
```php
<?php
declare(strict_types=1);
namespace App\Domain\Assets\Data;

use Spatie\LaravelData\Data;
use Spatie\LaravelData\Lazy;
use Spatie\LaravelData\DataCollection;

final readonly class AssetCollectionData extends Data
{
    public function __construct(
        public int                              $total,
        /** @var DataCollection<int, AssetTableData> */
        public Lazy|DataCollection              $items,
    ) {}
}
```

===============================================================================
PRINCIPLE 4 — LARAVEL PIPELINES
===============================================================================

Pipe classes live in  : App\Domain\{Module}\Pipelines\
Each pipe MUST be     : final class with handle(mixed $payload, \Closure $next): mixed
Pipes are             : infrastructure agnostic — no HTTP, no Request, no Response
Core Actions own      : the Pipeline::send()->through()->thenReturn() call

Use pipelines for:
  - Multi-stage data transformation
  - Validation chains with early exits
  - Enrichment / normalization flows
  - Multi-step document processing

EXAMPLE — Pipeline in Core Action:
```php
public function handle(AssetUpsertData $data): AssetTableData
{
    /** @var AssetUpsertData $processed */
    $processed = app(Pipeline::class)
        ->send($data)
        ->through([
            ValidateAssetCode::class,
            EnrichWithCategoryDefaults::class,
            NormalizeLocationData::class,
        ])
        ->thenReturn();

    $asset = Asset::updateOrCreate(['id' => $processed->id], $processed->toArray());

    return AssetTableData::fromModel($asset);
}
```

EXAMPLE — Pipe class:
```php
<?php
declare(strict_types=1);
namespace App\Domain\Assets\Pipelines;

use App\Domain\Assets\Data\AssetUpsertData;
use Closure;

final class NormalizeLocationData
{
    public function handle(AssetUpsertData $payload, Closure $next): mixed
    {
        $normalized = new AssetUpsertData(
            ...$payload->toArray(),
            location: strtoupper(trim($payload->location)),
        );

        return $next($normalized);
    }
}
```

===============================================================================
PRINCIPLE 5 — OCTANE SAFETY (FrankenPHP persistent state)
===============================================================================

Octane keeps the application alive between requests.
The following patterns cause memory leaks and stale-state bugs in production.

FORBIDDEN in any domain class:
  static mutable properties   → private static array $cache = []  (grows forever)
  Request stored in $this      → $this->request = $request  (stale on next request)
  Singleton state mutation     → modifying a bound singleton inside request cycle
  app()->instance() of stateful objects inside the request lifecycle

SAFE patterns:
  - All Actions, DTOs, ValueObjects, Pipes are stateless by design — keep them that way
  - Inject all dependencies as handle() parameters, never store in $this
  - Use Cache facade (Valkey) for shared state — never static properties
  - If per-request state is needed: bind it to the request lifecycle, not app lifecycle
  - Octane::table() for shared in-memory tables (read-heavy, rarely written)

===============================================================================
PRINCIPLE 6 — CROSS-CONTEXT COMMUNICATION
===============================================================================

Modules communicate ONLY through:
  1. Domain Events  → App\Domain\Shared\Events\*  — fire and let subscribers react
  2. Shared Action interfaces → App\Contracts\*  — dependency inversion
  3. Shared DTOs → App\Domain\Shared\Data\*  — explicit data contracts

NEVER:
  - Import a Model from another module
  - Call another module's Core Action directly from within a module
  - Define Eloquent relationships that cross module boundaries

Cross-context event example:
```php
// In Assets module — fires event, knows nothing about Maintenance
event(new AssetDecommissioned(assetId: $asset->id, decommissionedAt: now()));

// In Maintenance module — listens, reacts independently
final class CancelPendingWorkOrders
{
    use AsAction;
    use AsListener;

    public function handle(AssetDecommissioned $event): void
    {
        WorkOrder::pendingForAsset($event->assetId)->update(['status' => 'cancelled']);
    }
}
```

===============================================================================
PRINCIPLE 7 — MODELS (STRICTLY ANEMIC)
===============================================================================

Eloquent Models contain ONLY:
  $fillable, $casts, $table, $primaryKey, $connection
  Relationships : hasMany, belongsTo, morphTo, belongsToMany, etc.
  Query scopes  : scopeActive(), scopeByLocation(), scopeWithMedia(), etc.
  Attribute casts: protected $casts = ['status' => StatusEnum::class]
  Media registration: registerMediaCollections() for Spatie MediaLibrary
  Factory       : use HasFactory (for tests only)

NEVER in a Model:
  Business logic methods
  Service / action calls
  Calculation, processing, validation methods
  HTTP or notification logic

===============================================================================
PRINCIPLE 8 — HTMX + ALPINE.JS
===============================================================================

HTMX:
  - All server interactions go through hx-* attributes on Blade templates
  - Responses are Blade partials rendered via HtmxOrchestrator
  - Validation errors → HX-Trigger header → Notyf toast (NOT form swap for errors)
  - Multi-target updates → hx-swap-oob="true" on secondary fragments
  - Push history when appropriate → hx-push-url="true"

Alpine.js:
  - Client-side UI behavior ONLY: toggles, tabs, dropdowns, modals, animations
  - NEVER make server calls from Alpine (no fetch, no axios inside x-data)
  - NEVER put business logic in x-data
  - Delegate ALL server interaction to HTMX
  - Trigger HTMX from Alpine: $dispatch('htmx:trigger') or hx-trigger="custom-event"
  - Share UI state across components: Alpine.store('moduleName', { ... })

===============================================================================
WORKFLOW — HOW TO GENERATE CODE
===============================================================================

When receiving a task:

1. Identify the module and the layer (Core Action / Web Action / DTO / Pipe / Model)
2. HTMX feature    → Web Action (HtmxOrchestrator) + Core Action + DTO + Blade partial
3. Background task → Core Action with AsJob, PayloadData DTO
4. Event-driven    → Core Action with AsListener, domain event in Shared/Events
5. Complex logic   → Core Action orchestrates Pipeline, each step is a Pipe class
6. Always create the correct DTO suffix — never pass raw arrays between layers

Before submitting code, mentally run this checklist:
  [ ] declare(strict_types=1) at the top
  [ ] All names in ENGLISH
  [ ] Core Action: no HTTP, returns DTO
  [ ] Web Action: uses HtmxOrchestrator, delegates to Core Action
  [ ] DTO: final readonly class, correct suffix, fromModel() on TableData
  [ ] Pipe: final class, handle(mixed $payload, Closure $next): mixed
  [ ] Model: no business logic
  [ ] No Models in Views or Web/Api Actions
  [ ] No direct cross-module imports
  [ ] No static mutable properties (Octane safety)
  [ ] Store/Upsert Web Actions use ProtectAgainstSpam
  [ ] No manual HX-* header manipulation outside HtmxOrchestrator

